          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "QRxC9CySf0I2",
        "outputId": "3cc75530-1227-417e-f31a-e022dfed9516"
      },
      "execution_count": 19,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "Overfitting.  A fundamental concept in machine learning and data analysis.  As a teacher, I'd be happy to break it down for you.\n",
            "\n",
            "**What is overfitting?**\n",
            "\n",
            "Overfitting occurs when a machine learning model is too closely fit to the training data.  In other words, the model becomes too specialized in the data it was trained on and fails to generalize well to new, unseen data.  This results in poor performance on new data, even if the model performed exceptionally well on the training data.\n",
            "\n",
            "**Why does overfitting happen?**\n",
            "\n",
            "Overfitting happens for several reasons:\n",
            "\n",
            "1. **Model complexity**: When a model is too complex, it can fit the noise in the training data rather than the underlying patterns.  This means that the model is essentially memorizing the training data rather than learning generalizable relationships.\n",
            "2. **Insufficient training data**: When there is not enough training data, the model may not have enough information to learn generalizable patterns.  As a result, it may overfit the limited data it has.\n",
            "3. **Noise in the data**: Noisy data can cause a model to overfit, as the model tries to fit the random fluctuations in the data rather than the underlying patterns.\n",
            "\n",
            "**Consequences of overfitting**\n",
            "\n",
            "Overfitting can have serious consequences, including:\n",
            "\n",
            "1. **Poor predictive performance**: An overfit model will not perform well on new, unseen data.\n",
            "2. **Lack of generalizability**: An overfit model may not be able to generalize to different datasets or scenarios.\n",
            "3. **Wasted computational resources**: Overfitting can lead to wasted computational resources, as the model may require more computational power to train and deploy.\n",
            "\n",
            "**Techniques to prevent overfitting**\n",
            "\n",
            "Fortunately, there are several techniques to prevent overfitting, including:\n",
            "\n",
            "1. **Regularization**: Regularization techniques, such as L1 and L2 regularization, can help reduce the complexity of a model and prevent overfitting.\n",
            "2. **Early stopping**: Early stopping involves stopping the training process when the model's performance on the validation set starts to degrade.\n",
            "3. **Data augmentation**: Data augmentation involves generating additional training data through techniques such as rotation, flipping, and cropping.\n",
            "4. **Cross-validation**: Cross-validation involves splitting the available data into training and validation sets and evaluating the model's performance on the validation set.\n",
            "5. **Simplifying the model**: Simplifying the model by reducing the number of features or layers can help prevent overfitting.\n",
            "\n",
            "**Real-world example**\n",
            "\n",
            "Suppose we're trying to build a model to predict house prices based on features such as the number of bedrooms, square footage, and location.  If we train a model on a small dataset of houses in a specific neighborhood, the model may overfit to the data and perform poorly on houses in other neighborhoods.  To prevent overfitting, we could use regularization techniques, collect more data from different neighborhoods, or simplify the model by reducing the number of features.\n",
            "\n",
            "I hope this explanation helps you understand overfitting and how to prevent it.  Do you have any questions or would you like me to elaborate on any of the concepts?\n"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        " Step 8: Few-Shot Prompting\n",
        "Python"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "ArTbaTvobB0a"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "from langchain_core.prompts import FewShotPromptTemplate, PromptTemplate\n",
        "\n",
        "examples = [\n",
        "    {\"input\": \"I love this\", \"output\": \"Positive\"},\n",
        "    {\"input\": \"I hate this\", \"output\": \"Negative\"}\n",
        "]\n",
        "\n",
        "example_prompt = PromptTemplate(\n",
        "    input_variables=[\"input\", \"output\"],\n",
        "    template=\"Text: {input}\\nSentiment: {output}\"\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "few_shot_prompt = FewShotPromptTemplate(\n",
        "    examples=examples,\n",
        "    example_prompt=example_prompt,\n",
        "    prefix=\"Classify sentiment:\\n\\n\",\n",
        "    suffix=\"Text: {input}\\nSentiment:\",\n",
        "    input_variables=[\"input\"]\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "chain = few_shot_prompt | model\n",
        "\n",
        "response = chain.invoke({\"input\": \"This is amazing\"})\n",
        "print(response.content)"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "mlYzT02yg61e",
        "outputId": "c5bb4279-d6a5-4981-ed42-8fd03473caea"
      },
      "execution_count": 22,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "Positive\n"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
